Implementation

A custom script (daily-health-check.sh) was created to automate routine server inspections.

The script performs:

CPU load monitoring
Disk usage validation with warning thresholds
Memory availability checks
Swap monitoring
Docker container verification
Docker restart counter inspection
Nginx service validation
PostgreSQL service validation
Fail2ban jail status inspection
SSH and Nginx banned IP statistics
Application log analysis for recent errors
HTTP endpoint verification
Automatic infrastructure summary

The script was later enhanced with:

🟢 Healthy
🟡 Warning
🔴 Critical

status indicators, making the output much easier to interpret during routine maintenance.

Investigation Results

Running the health check confirmed:

Production server uptime exceeding 23 days
Very low CPU utilization
Stable memory consumption
Docker container running continuously with 0 restarts
Nginx and PostgreSQL operating normally
Fail2ban actively protecting both SSH and Nginx
No infrastructure failures detected

During log analysis, one application-level error was identified involving a duplicate invoice token. Investigation showed that the PostgreSQL unique constraint correctly prevented duplicate data insertion, confirming that the infrastructure remained healthy while the issue was isolated to application business logic.

Lessons Learned

This project demonstrated the importance of distinguishing between infrastructure failures and application-level issues.

Instead of reacting to every logged error as a server problem, I learned to:

verify service availability first;
inspect container health before debugging code;
validate security controls;
separate infrastructure responsibilities from application development.
Outcome

The server now has a reusable daily monitoring tool that reduces routine inspection time and provides a consistent overview of system health.

